        "eyebrow": "Book Reviews by Anmol Pushjai Goel",
        "heading": "One book at a time.",
        "description": "Long-form, unsentimental reviews — what the book broke, what it built, and whether it was worth the bruise. Ten so far, in his own hand.",
        "note": "Ten reviews and counting — tap any cover to read it in full.",
        "modal_kicker": "Book Review · Anmol Pushjai Goel",
        "download_label": "Download the original · public domain",
        "signature": "— Anmol Pushjai Goel",
        "reviews": [
          {
            "_key": "review-1",
            "title": "The Age of Surveillance Capitalism",
            "author": "Shoshana Zuboff",
            "year": "2019",
            "teaser": "There is a thing you do a hundred times a day and you think it is free. You search something. You tap accept. You let the…",
            "body": "There is a thing you do a hundred times a day and you think it is free. You search something. You tap accept. You let the map watch you walk. Free, you think. The deal is, I get the service and they get nothing, or maybe a little ad money, fair trade. Zuboff wrote seven hundred pages to tell you that you have completely misread the transaction. You are not the customer. You are not even the product, which is the lazy line everyone repeats. You are the raw material. You are the forest being logged, and your own behaviour, your face, your voice, your route to work, your hesitation before you click, is the timber. And nobody asked the forest.\n\nThat is the book. It is long, it is repetitive, it invents a new word every nine pages and half of them are clumsy, and underneath all of that it is one of the most important diagnoses of our time, because she is the one who finally named the machine instead of complaining about its side effects. Let me walk you through it, because almost everyone who quotes this book has read the title and the first chapter and quit.\n\nThe core definition. Say it slowly because everything hangs on it.\n\nSurveillance capitalism, she says, is the unilateral claiming of private human experience as free raw material for translation into behavioural data. Unpack that word by word. Unilateral, meaning nobody agreed, there was no negotiation, they just took it. Private human experience, meaning your life, the stuff that was nobody's business. Free, meaning they pay you nothing for it. Raw material, meaning you are a resource being mined, like coal, like oil, like a river they are allowed to poison because the law has not caught up to the fact that the river belongs to anyone.\n\nThis is the whole reframe and it is correct. Stop thinking about privacy. Privacy is the wrong frame, it makes it sound like a personal preference, like whether you keep your curtains open. This is not about privacy. This is about a new economic order that found a thing nobody had figured out how to own yet, which is human experience itself, and quietly claimed the deed to it.\n\nThe discovery. How Google fell into it by accident around 2001.\n\nThis is the best history in the book so slow down here. She tells the origin and it matters, because it shows the thing was not some grand evil plan, it was a desperate scramble that worked too well, which is somehow worse.\n\nEarly Google had a problem. Great search, no money, and after the dot com crash in 2000 the investors were about to walk. They were sitting on a mountain of what they thought was waste. Data exhaust. The leftover crumbs of how people searched, what they misspelled, how long they paused, what they clicked next, the digital sawdust of the search process. Google had always assumed this junk should be fed back to improve the service for the user, and a chunk of it was.\n\nThen they realised the junk was not junk. The exhaust could predict behaviour. And once you can predict what a person will do, you can sell that prediction to whoever wants the person to do it. She names the crumbs. Behavioural surplus. The surplus is the part of your data they take beyond what is actually needed to make the service work for you. That extra. That overage. That is the gold, and the entire industry is built on quietly extracting it while telling you it is all just to serve you better.\n\nThat is the original sin and she dates it precisely. The moment Google decided the surplus belonged to Google and not to you, and that they would not ask, and that they would hide the taking inside terms of service no human reads. The whole trillion dollar tower stands on that one unannounced decision.\n\nPrediction products and the behavioural futures market.\n\nFollow the money one step further. They take your surplus, they run it through their machine learning, and they manufacture prediction products. Forecasts of what you will do, buy, click, feel, vote.\n\nAnd then, the key move, they sell those predictions in what she calls behavioural futures markets. A market in bets on your future behaviour. The advertiser is not really buying an ad slot. He is buying a wager on your next action, a stake in your future, sold by a company that knows you better than your spouse and is gambling on you in a market you cannot see and were never told existed. You are the underlying asset in a derivatives market trading in your own life, collecting none of the winnings.\n\nThe extraction imperative. Why it can never stop.\n\nHere is why it gets worse forever and cannot self correct. Because prediction works better with more data, the entire model runs on one law she calls the extraction imperative. Get more. Always more. More of everyone, more of the time, from more places. There is no natural stopping point, no enough, no level of data at which the company says we have plenty now, leave the people alone. Competition guarantees the opposite. The one who extracts more predicts better and wins, so all of them are locked in a race to the bottom of your soul.\n\nThis is the part people miss. It is not that some companies are greedy and some are nice. The greed is structural. The model itself demands total extraction or death. A surveillance capitalist who respects your boundaries loses to one who does not. So they all stop respecting them. The system selects for the most invasive player every single time, the way the worst tourist behaviour selects itself when nobody faces consequences. The machine has an appetite and the appetite is its design, not its flaw.\n\nEconomies of action. The part that should scare you.\n\nUp to here they are watching and predicting. Now comes the line they cross, and she dates this to the moment predicting stopped being enough and they moved to causing.\n\nShe calls it economies of action. It is no longer enough to forecast what you will do. The really valuable product is making you do it, nudging, herding, tuning your actual behaviour toward the outcome the bettor paid for, and doing it so subtly you experience it as your own free choice.\n\nHer headline case is Pokémon Go, and it is the cleanest example anyone has produced. Looked like a cute game. Was actually a behaviour herding experiment at planetary scale. The lures and the rare creatures were placed to drive foot traffic to McDonald's, to Starbucks, to businesses paying for guaranteed human bodies to walk through their door. The players thought they were chasing Pikachu. They were cattle, and the game was the dog, and the farmer was a business you never saw being paid for your footsteps. That is the whole future in one game. Not predicting the herd. Steering it, while the herd feels free.\n\nBig Other, not Big Brother. Why this is not the dystopia we were warned about.\n\nThis is her sharpest conceptual move and the reason the book matters philosophically. We were all trained by Orwell to fear the wrong thing. We are watching for Big Brother, the state, the boot, the fear, the gulag, power that hurts you into obedience.\n\nThat is not this. This is something new she calls instrumentarian power, and its tool is not Big Brother but what she names Big Other. It does not care what you think. It does not want your soul or your loyalty or your terror. Totalitarianism wanted to own your inside, to make you love the Party. This thing has zero interest in your inside. It only wants your behaviour, reliable and predictable and tuneable, and it is perfectly happy for you to feel completely free while it shapes you. It does not break you. It does not need to. It just quietly engineers the conditions so you do the profitable thing and thank the app for the convenience.\n\nThis is genuinely original and genuinely frightening, because a tyranny that lets you feel free is far harder to revolt against than one that puts a boot on your face. You cannot rage against a boot you cannot feel. The cage is comfortable, climate controlled, and you helped build it one accepted cookie at a time.\n\nThe division of learning. The real political question.\n\nNear the end she lands the deepest point and it is the one to keep. Every society organises itself around a central question, and ours, she says, is the division of learning. Who knows. Who decides who knows. Who decides who decides.\n\nRight now the answer to all three is, them. A handful of companies know almost everything about almost everyone, they alone decide what is known and what stays hidden, and they alone decide who gets to decide. That is an unprecedented concentration of knowledge, and therefore of power, in private unelected hands, with no democratic check, no vote, no appeal. She is right that this is the political fact of the century and we are barely discussing it, because we are too busy enjoying the free maps.\n\nNow where the book is genuinely weak, because it is, and I am not going to gush.\n\nFirst, the prose. It is exhausting. She invents a small dictionary of new terms and repeats them like incantations, and a book that could have changed the world at three hundred pages instead buries its own argument under seven hundred. There is a real cost to this. The people who most needed to read it could not get through it, and so the idea reached fewer minds than its importance deserved. Brilliance that nobody can finish is brilliance with a leak in it.\n\nSecond, and this is the serious one, she lets capitalism itself off the hook. Her entire framing is that this is a rogue mutation, a hijacking, surveillance capitalism as opposed to some imagined healthy normal capitalism it deformed. That is a dodge. The Marxists hammered her on this and they were right to. Capitalism did not get hijacked. Capitalism did exactly what capitalism does, which is find the nearest unowned thing and enclose it, the way it enclosed common land and labour and the seas. Human experience was just the last commons standing, and it got fenced on schedule. By calling it rogue she protects the system that produced it and aims you at the symptom instead of the engine. She diagnoses the tumour and refuses to name the body it grew in.\n\nThird, like every great diagnostician, the prescription is a whisper. After seven hundred pages of overwhelming you with the machine, her answer is essentially that we need new laws, a new social movement, a reclaimed right to the future. Correct, and useless, because she does not tell you how a public this thoroughly herded and this addicted to the convenience is supposed to organise against the very thing tuning its behaviour. She proves the cage is total and then asks the cattle to vote their way out. Naming the disease at this length and handing over a pamphlet for the cure is becoming a genre, and she is one of its finest authors.\n\nThe part that is about us, which she barely touches and which is the whole story here.\n\nZuboff wrote this looking at America, where at least there is a fight, where there are hearings and journalists and the occasional regulator with teeth. Read it from India and it stops being a warning and becomes a description of a thing already finished, with nobody even pretending to resist.\n\nBecause we did not just open the door to surveillance capitalism. We built the door, paid for it with public money, and called it progress. We constructed the largest biometric database on the planet, Aadhaar, fingerprints and irises of more than a billion people, the exact raw material she spends seven hundred pages warning about, and we did it with the state's own hands and a smile. We built UPI, the most beautiful real time map of the financial behaviour of an entire civilisation, every transaction of a billion people flowing through pipes that someone can read. Jio walked in and gave away data for free, the oldest move in the book, the free service that is not free because you are the timber, and we celebrated it as a national triumph. Free, we said. Look how cheap our internet is. Free.\n\nShe describes companies quietly extracting behavioural surplus while hiding it in terms nobody reads. We went further. We made the surplus a public utility and mandated participation. You cannot get the ration, the gas, the SIM, the school admission without feeding the machine. In America the extraction is sold to you as convenience. Here it is a precondition of existing as a citizen. The state did not protect us from the machine. The state became the largest node of the machine and then handed the data architecture to private players through partnerships we were never shown.\n\nAnd here is the inversion she does not have a frame for, the same one that keeps recurring in this whole library. Her model assumes the danger is private capital and the hope is the democratic state. In India the state is the surveillance capitalist, or its landlord, and there is no second power to chain it, because the courts are slow, the press is tame, and the public, exactly as she predicted, is too pleased with the free convenience to ask who is logging the footsteps. The division of learning she fears, who knows, who decides who knows, who decides who decides, in India the answer to all three is a fused thing, state and corporate, with the citizen as pure raw material and no vote on any of it. We are not heading toward Big Other. We installed it ourselves, ahead of schedule, with subsidies, and threw a launch event.\n\nAnd remember the previous book in this stack, the one about the parking lot. We do not even own the model layer that will read all this data and turn it into prediction and then into herding. We supply the timber. The mill is in San Francisco, with a new lock on it as of last week. So the most complete behavioural map of human beings ever assembled, a billion lives, sits in a country that builds the data and rents the intelligence to process it. We are the forest, and we do not own the saw, and we do not own the mill, and we are clapping because the logging trucks run on free fuel.\n\nThe verdict.\n\nRead it. Push through the prose, skip the repetition, do not let the seven hundred pages and the jargon defeat you, because the core idea is one of the few genuinely new things anyone has said about how power works in this century, and once you see behavioural surplus and economies of action and Big Other, you cannot unsee them, and your relationship to every screen you own changes permanently. That is what a real book does.\n\nBut hold two things against it. She protects capitalism by calling its newest crime a deviation when it was a continuation, and she diagnoses a total system and then asks the people it has captured to politely reform it, which is the part she has no real answer for and pretends she does.\n\nAnd read it as an Indian with your eyes fully open, because she is describing, with seven hundred careful pages and a hundred new words, a building we already finished, paid for, mandated, and celebrated, while she was still warning her own country it might one day be built. The thing she fears is coming to America. It already moved in here, and we held the door, and we are smiling in the photo.\n\nI would love to be told we kept some sanctuary, some corner of the future tense that is still ours. Then I remember that to buy a phone in this country you press your fingerprint into a machine owned by people you will never meet, and that you do it gratefully, because the alternative is not existing. We did not lose the right to the future. We auctioned it, and the reserve price was free data.",
