            "teaser": "There is a particular kind of book that survives not by being read but by being invoked, and Annihilation of Caste has spent most of its…",
            "body": "There is a particular kind of book that survives not by being read but by being invoked, and Annihilation of Caste has spent most of its ninety years in that category. It is cited far more often than it is opened. This is unfortunate, because read plainly it remains one of the most rigorously argued works of social criticism the subcontinent has produced and one of the few that still cannot be comfortably answered.\n\nIts origin explains much of its force. The text was written in 1936 as a presidential address for the Jat-Pat-Todak Mandal, a group of Hindu reformers in Lahore who had themselves set out to abolish caste. When they read the draft and asked Ambedkar to moderate his conclusions, he declined to revise a single line, and the lecture was cancelled. He then published it at his own expense. The book we have, in other words, is a speech its commissioning audience could not bring itself to hear — a fact that turns out to be inseparable from its argument.\n\nThat argument proceeds with unusual economy. Ambedkar's first claim is definitional: caste is not, as its apologists insist, a division of labour but a division of labourers. A society may organise work without ranking the human beings who perform it; caste does precisely the second thing, fixing worth by birth into what he calls a system of graded inequality. The grading is the point. Because every stratum has another beneath it to despise, no stratum possesses a clean interest in dismantling the structure. Each participant is at once subordinate and superior, prisoner and warden. It is a closed system that reproduces its own consent.\n\nFrom this follows his central and most contested thesis: caste cannot be reformed, only abolished, because it is not finally a social custom but a religious belief. The Hindu observes caste, in his reading, not from cruelty but from conviction — because the Shastras are held to sanction it and the Shastras are held to be divine. So long as the scripture retains its sanctity, the hierarchy it ordains retains its sanctity too. The reformer who attacks the practice while leaving the authority of the texts intact is therefore treating a symptom and protecting the cause. The real target must be the doctrinal infallibility of the Vedas and Shastras themselves; the test of any social arrangement must be reason and utility, not divine sanction. His concluding declaration that he will not die a Hindu is often read as provocation, but within the architecture of the argument it is simply the last logical step.\n\nAmbedkar is careful to close the exits before his opponents reach them. Caste has not functioned as eugenics, since it has demonstrably not improved any human stock. It is not rational economic organisation, since it allocates occupation by birth rather than aptitude. And by fragmenting society into mutually indifferent groups, it produces a population incapable of the fellow-feeling on which any genuine nation depends — which grounds his insistence that social reform must precede political independence rather than follow it.\n\nThe appended exchange with Gandhi clarifies the stakes. Gandhi defended an idealised varna order: retain the fourfold scheme, remove the cruelty and untouchability attached to it. Ambedkar's response is that the scheme is the cruelty, and that a humane version of a hierarchy of birth is a contradiction in terms. The disagreement between the two men maps, almost exactly, onto a disagreement the country has never resolved.\n\nAs a piece of writing the book is austere rather than ornate. The prose is functional, declarative, lawyerly in the best sense — the instrument of a mind trained at Columbia and the London School of Economics applying evidence and logic to a subject usually defended by appeals to sentiment and antiquity. Readers expecting rhetorical grandeur will not find it; what they will find is a sustained refusal to grant any premise that cannot survive scrutiny. Its limitations are the limitations of its moment: the prescriptions are addressed to a 1930s reform debate, and the alternatives Ambedkar gestures toward are sketched more than developed. But these are the weaknesses of an occasional address, not of the analysis, which remains intact.\n\nWhat is most striking from the vantage of 2026 is how little of it has been refuted and how thoroughly it has been absorbed without being acted upon. The book's afterlife is itself a case study in the mechanism it describes. A text whose entire purpose was to deny scripture its untouchable authority has been turned, by the very society it indicted, into a kind of scripture of its own quoted, garlanded, and largely unread, its author monumentalised precisely so that his argument need not be confronted. The diagnosis has aged into something close to prophecy: Ambedkar warned that political freedom layered over an unreformed social order would merely hand the existing hierarchy a national flag, and that is a fair description of much that has happened since.\n\nThe verdict, then, is straightforward. As reasoning, Annihilation of Caste is close to flawless and remains unanswered on its own terms. As literature it is plain and unsentimental, which suits it. And as a mirror it is genuinely difficult to sit with, which is the likeliest explanation for why a country that claims to revere its author has so carefully avoided reading him. It is essential precisely because it is uncomfortable and it earns the rare distinction of being a ninety-year-old polemic that the present has not yet caught up to.",
