            "_key": "review-3",
            "title": "Capitalism and Freedom",
            "author": "Milton Friedman",
            "year": "1962",
            "teaser": "There is a belief so deep in the modern mind that most people do not even know it is a belief. That a good government, a…",
            "body": "There is a belief so deep in the modern mind that most people do not even know it is a belief. That a good government, a caring government, should step in and fix things. Help the poor, run the schools, control the rents, license the doctors, set the wages, steer the economy with a wise hand. We treat this as simple decency, the obvious meaning of a society that gives a damn. Friedman wrote this book in 1962 to tell you that almost every one of those caring interventions is a quiet theft of your freedom, that the wise hand is usually a clumsy fist, and that the market you have been taught to distrust is in fact the single greatest protector of human liberty ever discovered. He is the most powerful enemy of the assumptions most decent people hold, and the reason you have to read him is that he is far harder to dismiss than you want him to be.\n\nThis is the book that armed a revolution. Reagan, Thatcher, the whole turn toward deregulation and privatisation and free markets that ran the world from 1980 onward, it is all downstream of this slim volume and the man who wrote it. To understand the world you live in, including the world the previous books in this stack were furious about, you have to understand the argument that built it, made in its clearest and most honest form, which is here.\n\nThe core claim. Economic freedom is political freedom. They cannot be separated.\n\nStart with the foundation, because everything is built on it and most critics never actually engage it.\n\nFriedman's central argument is that economic freedom is not just nice to have alongside political freedom. It is a precondition of political freedom. They are not two separate things. One makes the other possible.\n\nHere is the logic, and it is tighter than its enemies admit. Political freedom means you can dissent, organise, publish, oppose the people in power. But to do any of that you need resources outside the control of those people. If the state owns everything, the jobs, the printing presses, the meeting halls, the money, then the dissident has a problem that has nothing to do with laws about free speech. Where does he get a job after he opposes the government, when the government is the only employer? Who prints his pamphlet, when the state owns the presses? Who rents him a hall, when the state owns the buildings? In a fully socialist economy, Friedman says, free speech is a paper right, because the material base required to exercise it is entirely in the hands of the people you want to criticise.\n\nThe market solves this without anyone intending to. In a capitalist economy, power is dispersed. There are many employers, many printers, many landlords, many sources of money, and crucially they do not coordinate and do not care about your politics, they care about your money. The racist will still sell to the person he hates because the cash is green. The capitalist will print the communist's pamphlet because printing pays. The market is impersonal, and that impersonality is a shield. It lets the dissident survive by separating his economic life from his political opinions. The free market, Friedman argues, is the greatest engine of tolerance ever built, not because capitalists are virtuous but because the profit motive does not check your beliefs at the door.\n\nThis is a serious argument and you cannot wave it away with a slogan. The 20th century is largely on his side here. The regimes that owned the whole economy did, in fact, crush dissent with a totality no market society matched, because they controlled the bread as well as the ballot. Anyone who wants to refute Friedman has to deal with this, and most of his casual critics never do.\n\nThe role of government. What the state is actually for.\n\nHe is not an anarchist, and pretending he is misses the book, so be precise here.\n\nFriedman gives government real, necessary jobs. It must provide a legal framework, enforce contracts, define and protect property rights, maintain law and order, run national defence, provide a stable currency, and address genuine cases where markets cannot function, like true natural monopolies and real neighbourhood effects, what economists call externalities. He is a minimal state man, not a no state man. The state is the umpire. It sets and enforces the rules of the game. What it must not do is also play the game, pick the winners, or override the free choices of individuals in the name of helping them.\n\nThe book is essentially a long, specific, relentless application of one test to one government activity after another. Does this intervention pass? Is it a true rule of the game, or is it the state overriding free choice and concentrating power that belongs dispersed? And one by one, he runs the activities through and finds most of them guilty.\n\nThe demolitions. Where the book gets specific and dangerous.\n\nThis is what makes it more than philosophy. He names real policies, things everyone assumed were good, and dismantles them, and several of these have aged into orthodoxy precisely because his logic was hard to beat.\n\nOccupational licensing. We assume requiring a licence to practise medicine, law, a trade, protects the public. Friedman says look closer. Licensing is usually a racket run by the existing practitioners to restrict entry, limit competition, and keep their own incomes high, dressed up as public safety. The doctors' guild controls who gets to be a doctor, keeps the numbers low, keeps the fees high, and calls it protecting patients. It is producers protecting producers at the consumer's expense, and it hurts most the poor who can no longer afford the inflated price of the protected service. He would rather you certify, give people information, and let them choose, than license, which forbids the choice entirely.\n\nPublic housing, minimum wage, and much of the welfare apparatus. He argues these often hurt the very people they claim to help. The minimum wage, in his analysis, does not raise the wage of the low skilled worker, it prices him out of a job entirely, because an employer will not pay more than the work produces, so the worker whose labour is worth less than the legal minimum simply does not get hired, and the law meant to help him has made him unemployable. The minimum wage, he says coldly, causes unemployment among exactly the people it was sold as protecting.\n\nThe licensing of the airwaves, tariffs, agricultural price supports, rent control, the regulation of industry, he runs through them all, and the pattern is always the same. A policy sold as protecting the public turns out, on inspection, to protect a producer interest, concentrate power, reduce freedom, and harm the poor it claimed to serve.\n\nThe famous solutions. Where he stops just criticising and builds.\n\nHe is not only a wrecker, and the constructive proposals are why the book outlived the moment, because several of them got adopted across the political spectrum.\n\nThe negative income tax. Instead of the vast tangled bureaucracy of welfare programmes, each with its own staff, rules, and humiliations, just give poor people money directly through the tax system, below a certain income the tax flows to you instead of from you. It is efficient, it respects the dignity and choice of the poor by trusting them to spend their own money, and it abolishes the welfare bureaucracy. This idea, from a free market conservative, is the direct ancestor of universal basic income, which the left now champions. That tells you the book is not the cartoon its enemies imagine.\n\nSchool vouchers. The state, he argues, has good reason to fund education but no good reason to run the schools. So fund the child, not the school. Give every parent a voucher worth the cost of educating their child, and let them spend it at any school they choose, public or private. The schools then compete for students, the good ones grow, the bad ones close, and the power moves from the state bureaucracy to the parent. Choice and competition, applied to education. This idea has been fought over for sixty years and is still live in every education debate on earth.\n\nThese two ideas alone show the method. Where the state has a legitimate goal, fund the individual and let choice and competition do the work, rather than build a state monopoly to deliver it. Trust the chooser, not the planner.\n\nNow the turn, because the book has been answered by history as much as by argument.\n\nEverything above is the strongest case for the market ever made plainly, and I have laid it out at full strength on purpose, because the lazy thing is to sneer at Friedman and the honest thing is to admit large parts of him were right. The socialist economies did crush freedom. Licensing often is a racket. Welfare bureaucracies often are degrading and inefficient. Markets often do disperse power in useful ways. Grant all of it. Now here is where it breaks.\n\nThe deepest flaw is the one the entire rest of this stack was built to expose. Friedman's whole argument rests on the premise that the market disperses power, that there are many employers, many printers, many sellers, none coordinating, and that this dispersal is what protects you. But what happens when the market itself produces monopoly? What happens when the free competition he loves is won, finally and totally, by a handful of players who then own the printing press, the marketplace, the town square, the very infrastructure of speech, not as a state but as private lords? Read Friedman right after Thiel and the floor gives way. Thiel told the founders to escape competition and build a monopoly. They did. And the dispersed market that was supposed to be Friedman's shield against tyranny congealed into exactly the concentration he said only the state could create, except now it is private, unelected, and answers to no constitution. Friedman never seriously reckoned with the market generating its own Leviathans. He spent the whole book watching the state and left the back door wide open, and the tech feudalism we now live under walked in through it. The dispersal he promised was temporary. The concentration is permanent.\n\nSecond, the freedom he defends is purely negative, freedom from coercion, and he refuses to take seriously that unfreedom can come from need as well as from force. He says you are free because no one is pointing a gun at you. But the man who must take any job at any wage to feed his children because the alternative is his children starving is, in every meaningful sense, coerced, just not by a person. The market coerces through hunger, and Friedman defines that coercion out of existence by insisting only the state, only a deliberate human hand, can truly make you unfree. This is a choice, not a discovery. He narrows the meaning of freedom until it fits the answer he wanted, and a great deal of real human suffering disappears into the gap between freedom from the state and freedom from desperation.\n\nThird, the minimum wage and welfare arguments are cleaner on the page than in the world. Sixty years of evidence on the minimum wage is genuinely mixed, and the simple it just causes unemployment story he tells has not held up as cleanly as he asserted it, because real labour markets have power imbalances, employers with leverage over workers, that his frictionless model assumes away. The model is elegant. The world has friction he priced at zero.\n\nThe part that is about us.\n\nBring it to India, because this book was used here, and the using is the story.\n\nThe 1991 liberalisation, the moment India tore down the licence raj, is Friedman vindicated, and I will say it plainly because it is true. The licence raj was occupational licensing and industrial regulation taken to its absolute Friedmanite nightmare, a state that decided who could make what, how much, at what price, a bureaucracy that strangled enterprise and, exactly as he predicted, protected a cosy club of incumbent producers while the poor paid for the inefficiency and waited years for a telephone. When we dismantled it, growth exploded, hundreds of millions rose, and that is a real debt the country owes to the argument in this book. Anyone in India who dismisses Friedman wholesale has to explain why removing precisely the controls he attacked produced precisely the liberation he promised. It did. Credit where due.\n\nBut now read the second half of our own story through the second half of his flaw, and it is devastating. We took Friedman's medicine for the licence raj, the state monopoly, and we were right to. But we never built the one thing he did require, the strong umpire, the state that enforces the rules of the game even as it stops playing. We got the deregulation and skipped the rule of law. So we did not get his clean competitive market. We got the worst of both, a state too weak to be a fair umpire and markets concentrated enough to become private rajas. The licence raj of the bureaucrat was replaced, in too many sectors, by the monopoly of the tycoon, the same dispersal of state power followed by a brutal re concentration in private hands, the exact failure mode Friedman could not see. We swapped a public Leviathan we could at least vote against for private ones we cannot. Friedman freed us from the bureaucrat and handed us, because he never guarded that door, to the oligarch.\n\nAnd here is the final Indian cut. Friedman's whole system assumes the impersonal market, the seller who does not care who you are because your money is green, as the great engine of tolerance. We established many books ago that India is the highest kinship intensity, most identity saturated civilisation on earth, where the market is not impersonal, where caste decides who rents to whom, who lends to whom, who hires whom, who marries whom. Friedman's tolerance machine runs on impersonality, and we feed it a society where almost nothing economic is impersonal. So the shield he promised, the market that does not check your identity at the door, barely functions here, because here the market checks your surname first. His mechanism requires the one psychological trait our operating system was built to destroy. The free market as a solvent of prejudice assumes people who will deal with the stranger. We are the people who will not.\n\nThe verdict.\n\nRead it. It is the clearest, most honest, most intellectually serious case for the free market and the minimal state ever written, and you cannot understand the modern world, including everything the angrier books in this stack were raging against, without first understanding this, because this is the operating manual the winners used. Friedman is not a fool or a shill, he is a first rate mind making a genuinely powerful argument, and large parts of it are simply correct, the dangers of the all owning state, the rackets hiding inside good intentions, the dignity of giving the poor money and choice rather than bureaucracy and instruction. You will be a sharper thinker for having been forced to answer him instead of dismissing him.\n\nBut read him knowing what his argument became when it won. He spent a brilliant book guarding the front door against the tyranny of the state and never noticed the market quietly building its own tyranny in the back, the private monopoly, the lord who owns the press and the square without needing an election, the concentration he swore only governments could achieve. The dispersed market was real and it was a shield, for exactly as long as it stayed dispersed. Then his own disciple Thiel told everyone the goal was to make it un dispersed, to escape competition and own the market forever, and the shield became a cathedral with a lawyer at the door. Friedman is right about the disease of the state and blind to the disease of the market, and we are now dying of the one he could not see.\n\nI would love to report that the liberalisation he inspired gave India a free and competitive market that disperses power and protects the small. Look at how many of our critical sectors are now controlled by a handful of names, ask whether power got dispersed or merely changed owners, and listen to the answer. We escaped the licence raj. We did not escape the raj. We just stopped electing it.",
            "pdf": ""
          },
