            "teaser": "Read it out loud and you will notice something before you notice anything else. It does not argue. It chants. Line after line begins with the…",
            "body": "Read it out loud and you will notice something before you notice anything else. It does not argue. It chants. Line after line begins with the same two words, we believe, we believe, we believe, hammered down the page like a drumbeat, and by the fortieth repetition you realise you are not reading an essay, you are reading a creed. This is a catechism. A man who owns a large slice of the future sat down and wrote scripture for it, and the format is not an accident, because you do not argue a faith, you recite it, and Andreessen does not want to convince you. He wants you to kneel.\n\nThat is the first and last thing to understand about this document. I spent a whole piece once arguing that this country was manufactured to choose faith over reason, that we were built to recite rather than question. Then I read the most powerful men in the richest valley on earth, the supposed high church of rationality and evidence and first principles, and found them doing the exact same thing. Replacing reason with a creed. Replacing argument with belief. Same disease the WhatsApp uncle has. Nicer font. Better yacht.\n\nLet me walk you through what it actually says, at full strength, because the lazy move is to laugh at a billionaire's poetry and the honest move is to admit the thing is doing real ideological work and a lot of people you know now believe it without knowing where they got it.\n\nThe setup. We are being lied to.\n\nIt opens, cleverly, as a rebellion. We have been told a lie, it says, the lie that technology is dangerous, that growth is bad, that progress costs us our souls and our jobs and our planet, that we should feel guilt and shame about building things. A whole culture of fear and limits and apology has captured us. And the manifesto announces itself as the liberation from that lie, the voice that finally says no, technology is good, growth is good, building is good, stop apologising and start making.\n\nNotice the move, because it is the engine of the whole thing. He casts the most powerful and richest faction in human history, the Silicon Valley capital machine, as the brave rebel against an oppressive orthodoxy. The lords are the underdogs. The people who own the cathedral are being persecuted, they say, by the people asking whether the cathedral should have a fire exit. Hold that, because it returns.\n\nThe core creed. Technology is the source of everything good.\n\nThen the litany proper. The central belief, stated many ways, is that technology is the prime mover of human progress and that essentially everything good in human life is downstream of it. Wealth, health, longer life, less hunger, less misery, all of it, the gift of technology and the growth that technology drives. Therefore more technology is more good, always, and anything that slows technology is, by simple arithmetic, killing the future humans who would have been saved by it.\n\nHe fuses three older ideas into one creed and you should name them so you see the join. From Schumpeter, creative destruction, the new killing the old as the source of all progress, which we already met in Thiel. From Julian Simon, the idea that human ingenuity is the ultimate resource, that there is no real scarcity because a free mind always invents its way out, which is his answer to every Malthusian, every doomer, every person who says we will run out. And from Friedman, the free market as the great coordinating miracle, the techno capital machine, his phrase, the engine that takes human creativity and turns it into abundance for all. Stack those three and you get the manifesto. It is not new. It is the previous two books in this stack set to music and stripped of every doubt either of them still had.\n\nAnd the boldest line of the faith, the one to actually sit with. He claims there is no material problem that more technology cannot solve. None. Energy, hunger, disease, poverty, all of it, just engineering problems awaiting enough innovation. It is a genuinely clarifying belief because it is falsifiable and total. Either you think human ingenuity has no ceiling, or you do not, and he plants his flag on no ceiling.\n\nEnergy and abundance. The one part that is mostly right.\n\nCredit where it is due, because the easy thing is to hate all of it and that is dishonest. The manifesto's demand for energy abundance is correct and bracing. It argues we should want vastly more energy, not less, that energy is the master resource, that a richer world is a higher energy world, and that the cult of energy scarcity, the instinct that the moral thing is always to use less, is a poverty mindset that condemns the poor to stay poor. It is loudly pro nuclear, pro building, pro abundance, against the reflexive degrowth idea that virtue means shrinking. On this, he is right, and most of his enemies are wrong, and a country with six hundred million people who deserve far more energy than they have should hear this part clearly and not let the rest of the manifesto's nonsense poison a true thing.\n\nThe enemies list. Where the mask slips.\n\nAnd then comes the part that gives the whole game away, the section that named names and got the document torn apart on arrival, and rightly.\n\nHe lists the enemy. Out loud. By name. And the enemy, in this manifesto, is not poverty, not disease, not ignorance, not the actual dragons. The enemy is the brakes. He names, as the things standing between humanity and paradise, ideas like sustainability, like tech ethics, like trust and safety, like risk management, like the precautionary principle, like the very concept of existential risk. The enemy, in plain words, is anyone who asks the question, wait, should we, anyone who suggests that a technology this powerful might need a seatbelt.\n\nRead that and understand what you are looking at. A man whose business is funding the most powerful technologies on earth has written a public creed declaring that caution itself, the act of asking whether a thing is safe before you ship it to eight billion people, is the enemy of humanity. He took the fire alarm and put it on the villains list. He looked at the one human instinct that might slow the machine he profits from, the instinct to check, to test, to be careful, and he labelled it evil and called the labelling optimism.\n\nThis is the toilet again. The whole document is engineered so your eyes never go to the place the harm actually lands. He floods you with the abundance, the cures, the saved children, the Promethean glory, and he very carefully files the brakes, the people who ask about the downstream, under enemy, so you never look down the pipe. The extraction is real. It just happens one layer below where the manifesto points your eyes, and the manifesto's entire job is to point your eyes up at the cathedral and away from the basement where the rent gets collected.\n\nThe patron saints, and the name he should not have written.\n\nHe also lists his patron saints of techno optimism, a pantheon, and most of it is the expected crowd, Nietzsche, the prophets of will and growth and overcoming. But he reached, infamously, for the Italian Futurists and quoted their spirit approvingly, and the Futurists, whose leader Marinetti went on to co write the literal manifesto of Italian Fascism, are not a footnote you include by accident. You can argue he meant only their love of speed and machines and the future. But when your gospel of unconstrained power, anti caution, anti limits, will to build, reaches instinctively for the aesthetic that fed into actual fascism, that is not a coincidence to wave away. It is the document showing you, in its choice of ancestors, what family of ideas it actually belongs to. Worship of force that calls its critics weak has a lineage, and he picked up the phone and called it.\n\nNow the turn, and I am going to be precise, because this is the capstone of everything before it.\n\nTake this manifesto and lay it next to the two books that came right before it in this stack, and the picture completes itself with a click you can almost hear.\n\nFriedman made the honest case. Markets disperse power, and dispersed power protects freedom, and the all owning state is the enemy of liberty. A real argument, large parts true, made by a serious man who at least submitted his claims to evidence and lost some of them to history.\n\nThiel made the honest confession. Competition is for losers, the goal is monopoly, escape the market, own the one thing that matters and never let go. Cold, but honest. He told you exactly what the winners want and did not pretend it was for you.\n\nAnd Andreessen is what comes after the confession. He is the propaganda. He takes Thiel's monopoly machine and Friedman's market and wraps the whole thing in wet eyed scripture about saving humanity, and he does the one thing neither of the others had the dishonesty to do. He claims the machine that concentrates all the power is the most pro human force there is, and he claims the people asking it to be careful are the enemy of the species. Friedman thought markets disperse power. Thiel admitted the goal is to concentrate it. Andreessen watched the concentration happen, the cathedral get built, the off switch end up in four buildings, and wrote a hymn declaring the concentration is liberation and the hymn is rebellion.\n\nI described this exact man in my own piece on tech feudalism without knowing I was describing a real document. The lord who goes on stage with wet sincere eyes and tells you it is the opposite of what it is. Open source, he says. The great equalizer. Intelligence in every pocket. More democratic than anything in history. This manifesto is that speech, written down, signed, and posted with pride. It is the cathedral describing itself as a public park. It is the man who owns the saw explaining to the forest that logging is the highest form of love.\n\nAnd here is the deepest dishonesty, the one that connects to my own oldest obsession. The manifesto poses as the triumph of reason over the fearful, superstitious doomers. Reason, evidence, first principles, the brave clear eyed builders against the hand wringing mystics. But it is not reason. It is a creed. We believe, we believe, we believe. It asserts that there is no problem technology cannot solve as an article of faith, not a finding. It declares caution evil by decree, not by argument. It hands you a list of saints and a list of demons and asks for your devotion. The richest rationalists on earth, faced with a genuinely hard question about a genuinely dangerous technology, did not reason. They wrote a religion, complete with a creation story, commandments, heretics, and a promised land. Faith over reason is not a third world disease. It is the operating system of the people who told you they were running on reason, and the proof is that their founding document is structured exactly like a prayer.\n\nWhere it is weak, beyond the dishonesty.\n\nStrip the propaganda and the actual argument has real holes, and name them.\n\nThe no problem technology cannot solve claim is the load bearing wall and it is hollow at the centre, because most of our hardest problems are not technical, they are problems of distribution, power, and who decides. We can already grow enough food and people still starve, not for lack of a better seed but because of who owns the land and the price. Technology does not solve the political question of who gets the abundance, and the manifesto's entire trick is to convert every political question, every question of power and justice, into a mere engineering question, because engineering questions have no villains and political questions point straight at him. It is the culturalisation of politics from the Žižek review, run in reverse. Recode the fight over power as a fight over technical progress, and the man with the power wins by default.\n\nAnd the manifesto never once turns its gaze on the machine it worships to ask what happens when the techno capital machine produces not abundance for all but a permanent gap, a few lords and a planet of tenants. It cannot ask, because the answer is in the mirror. It assumes the abundance flows down. Every book before it in this stack showed the abundance pools at the top and the bill flows down. He wrote a theory of who gets the future that conveniently forgets to mention who owns it.\n\nThe part that is about us.\n\nBring it home, because this manifesto landed in India harder than almost anywhere, and the landing is its own small tragedy.\n\nThis is the document, more than any other, that became the background music of Indian startup and venture culture, the vibe at every Bangalore conference, the energy behind every it is India's decade declaration. The swagger, the build build build, the optimism, the contempt for the cautious, the founder as hero conquering the future, all of it is downstream of this gospel, often quoted by people who never read it and could not tell you it was Andreessen who scored their entire worldview. We imported the creed wholesale, the way we import everything, one to n, a copy of a copy of someone else's faith.\n\nAnd the import is grotesque, because the manifesto is the gospel of the conqueror, and we read it cast as the conquered. It says we are not victims, we are conquerors, and a country that is the raw material of the data economy, that does not own a single frontier lab, that supplies the timber and rents the saw, read that line and cosplayed conqueror. We adopted the conqueror's swagger while occupying the colony's position. The lord wrote a hymn about owning the future and the tenant learned it by heart and sang it at his own eviction.\n\nThen the cruellest detail. The manifesto names the precautionary principle, safety, ethics, risk management as the enemy, the brakes that must be torn out. Fine. But you can only heroically rip out brakes you actually have. The West built a whole apparatus of safety, regulation, ethics review, and Andreessen is raging against it because it exists and it slows him. India never built any of it. We have almost no real tech safety regime, no serious data protection enforcement, no functioning apparatus of caution, as the surveillance review showed, we mandated the extraction and called it a public utility. So we imported a manifesto whose entire heroism is the removal of brakes, into a vehicle that was manufactured without brakes in the first place. We adopted the rebellion against safety in a country that has no safety to rebel against. We are flooring a car with no seatbelt, no airbag, no road, and reciting a Californian poem about the tyranny of seatbelts.\n\nAnd the final cut, against my own oldest line. I once wrote that optimism without honest diagnosis is just denial wearing a kurta. This manifesto is that sentence's purest specimen. It is pure optimism with the diagnosis surgically removed, optimism as a refusal to look, optimism deployed precisely so you do not ask who owns the machine or where the harm lands or why the gap is a sea. Set it beside Henrich, the one genuinely hopeful book in this whole stack, and the difference is everything. Henrich earned his hope through seven hundred pages of evidence, mechanism, and honest doubt, and his optimism is fragile and conditional and true. Andreessen's optimism is a chant that begins with we believe and never once stops to check whether the belief survives contact with the world. One is hope. The other is denial in a better font. Henrich gives you a reason to think the cage can be opened. Andreessen gives you a reason to stop noticing you are in one.\n\nThe verdict.\n\nRead it, and read it as primary source, not as philosophy, because as philosophy it is thin and as a document of power it is priceless. It is the clearest statement we have of what the lords of this century actually believe, or at least what they want you to believe they believe, and you cannot understand the people building the systems that will run your life without reading their creed in their own hand. It is short. Read it in twenty minutes. Then read it again and watch the structure, the chant, the enemies list, the wet eyed rebellion of the most powerful faction alive, and you will never again mistake this worldview for the neutral voice of progress it pretends to be.\n\nIt is right about energy and abundance and the poverty of the degrowth instinct, and a poor country should steal that part without apology. It is dishonest about almost everything else, and its central dishonesty is the one I keep returning to across every book in this stack. It takes a question about power, who owns the machine, who gets the future, who holds the off switch, and disguises it as a question about progress, where the only villains are the cowards who want to slow down. It is the gospel that makes the cathedral look like a gift.\n\nThe honest version of this document already exists, by the way. Thiel wrote it. The goal is monopoly, the goal is to escape competition, the goal is to own the one thing that matters and never let go. Andreessen took that confession, removed the honesty, added the wet eyes and the saved children and the chanting, and called the result optimism. It is the same machine. The same concentration. The same sea widening for the poor. He just set it to a hymn and put the people holding the fire alarm on the list of demons.\n\nI would love to be wrong about him. I would love to believe the man writing we are not victims, we are conquerors meant me, meant us, meant the kid in the district school with one teacher for sixty children. But you do not get to be a conqueror in someone else's creed, written by a man who already owns the field, sung to you on your way to becoming the most well behaved, most grateful, most photographed tenant on the estate. The manifesto is not addressed to us. We are not in the we that believes. We are the abundance the we intends to distribute, on terms we do not set, from a machine we do not own, and the document's genius is that it got us to chant along anyway.\n\nWe believe, we believe, we believe. We do. That was always the problem.",
