            "teaser": "There is a sentence everybody in this country says to their kid and thinks it is love. Study hard, get the marks, you can become anything.…",
            "body": "There is a sentence everybody in this country says to their kid and thinks it is love. Study hard, get the marks, you can become anything. Work hard enough and you will rise. It is the kindest sounding lie a parent can tell, and Sandel wrote a whole book to explain why it is a lie and why it has quietly poisoned every rich democracy on earth. The genius of the book is that it does not attack the losers' resentment, which is the easy target. It attacks the winners' pride, which nobody dares touch, because the winners write the books.\n\nLet me walk you through what he actually argues, chapter by chapter, because the argument is tight and most people who praise this book have only absorbed the title.\n\nThe setup. What meritocracy actually promises.\n\nStart with the thing itself, because people confuse it. Meritocracy is not the claim that talented people should do important jobs. Obviously the surgeon should be skilled. Sandel is not arguing for stupid pilots. The thing he is dissecting is the moral story bolted on top. The story that says where you end up is what you deserve. That success is earned and therefore the successful are entitled to it, and by the exact same logic, failure is also earned, and the failures deserve their failure too.\n\nThat second half is the poison and almost nobody notices it when they sign up for the first half. You cannot say the winner earned the top without also saying the loser earned the bottom. The same machine that hands the doctor his pride hands the unemployed man his shame. They come from one sentence. You buy them together.\n\nThe credentialism chapter. The diploma as the new caste mark.\n\nThis is one of the strongest sections so slow down here.\n\nSandel shows how the meritocratic society quietly turned the university degree into a sorting gate for human worth. Not just for jobs. For dignity. The credentialed look at the non credentialed and feel, somewhere underneath the politeness, that these people simply did not try hard enough. He digs up the actual data on what he calls credentialism, the last acceptable prejudice. Educated elites who would never sneer at someone for race or religion will sneer at someone for being uneducated without a flicker of guilt, because in the meritocratic faith, being uneducated is a moral failing, not an accident of birth. You earned your ignorance. Sit in it.\n\nAnd then the killer point. The politicians stopped offering people justice and started offering them a ladder. The whole liberal answer to inequality became, get yourself educated, retrain, upskill, rise. Which sounds generous and is actually contempt, because it tells the man whose factory closed that the solution is to become a different person. It locates the failure in him. It says the system is fine, you are the defect, go fix yourself. He calls this the rhetoric of rising and he shows it coming out of the mouths of Obama, Clinton, Blair, the entire centre left, who genuinely believed they were helping while they were busy telling half their country that their lives were their own fault.\n\nThe hubris chapter. Why the winners cannot help being insufferable.\n\nHere he turns the knife on his own class, which is the bravest thing in the book and the reason it is worth reading.\n\nThe meritocrat believes he made himself. Self made. And that belief, Sandel argues, kills two things. It kills gratitude, because if you did it all yourself you owe nobody, not your parents, not your teachers, not the society that built the school, not pure dumb luck. And it kills humility, because the flip side of I earned this is they failed to. The successful end up morally certain they deserve everything they have, and that certainty makes them blind and arrogant in a very specific way. They cannot see the luck. The being born to the right family, in the right country, with a brain the market happens to reward this decade. None of that is earned. You did not pick your parents, your genes, your era, or the fact that the economy currently pays coders and not coal miners. The talents you have are a gift. The fact that your society values those particular talents is a second gift. The meritocrat banks both and calls the total his own achievement.\n\nThis is the moral heart of the book. The problem with meritocracy is not that it fails to live up to its promise. The problem is what happens when it succeeds. Even a perfect meritocracy, where everybody truly rose or fell purely on talent and effort, would be a cruel society, because it would convince the winners they are gods and the losers they are garbage, and both would be lying to themselves about luck.\n\nThe Brexit and Trump chapter. The bill comes due.\n\nSandel reads the populist explosion of 2016 not as racism alone, though he does not deny that, but as the revenge of the people the meritocracy humiliated. For decades you told them the system was fair and open, that anyone could rise. Then you arranged the economy so they could not, and you topped it off by telling them their failure to rise was a personal and moral one. You took their jobs and then you took their dignity and then you had the nerve to act surprised when they voted to burn the whole thing down.\n\nThis is the part of the book that has aged into prophecy. He is essentially explaining 2016 to liberals who still, in 2020, did not understand that the contempt was the cause. The populist did not necessarily offer those people a better economic deal. He offered them something the meritocrats refused to, which was respect. He told them their work mattered, their place mattered, they were not stupid for not having a Yale degree. It was often a con. It worked anyway, because it was the only side talking to them like human beings instead of like a retraining problem.\n\nThe solutions chapter. Where it gets thin.\n\nNow the honest part, because I am not going to pretend the back half is as strong as the front.\n\nSandel's diagnosis is a scalpel. His prescription is a butter knife. He proposes, among other things, a lottery for elite university admissions. Set a threshold, take everyone qualified above it, and then draw names from a hat, which would at least strip the winners of the delusion that they were chosen for their sacred specialness. It is actually a clever idea precisely because it destroys the moral story, the kid knows he got lucky, the luck is admitted out loud. But it is one fix for one symptom. He talks about the dignity of work, about rebuilding respect for jobs that do not require a degree, about taxing finance and valuing labour. All correct. All gestured at. None of it built into anything a government could pick up on Monday morning.\n\nThis is the standard disease of the brilliant diagnostician. He can describe the cancer cell by cell. When you ask for the treatment he hands you a pamphlet about eating well.\n\nThe verdict.\n\nThe first two thirds of this book are essential and close to unanswerable. Sandel does the one thing almost no public intellectual has the nerve to do, he indicts the winners instead of flattering them, he tells the educated liberal reader, who is exactly the person buying this book, that his pride is unearned and his compassion is condescension. That takes guts and it is correct.\n\nNow let me say the thing Sandel, an American writing for Americans, does not have to face, but we do.\n\nRead this book in India and it stops being theory and starts being a confession. Because we did not just import meritocracy. We poured it on top of caste, which is the oldest tyranny of inherited rank on the planet, and produced something genuinely poisonous. The JEE rank, the UPSC result, the IIT tag, these are not just career sorters here. They have become a new clean modern sounding language to do the exact thing the caste system always did, rank human beings by worth and call the ranking deserved. The upper caste kid with the tutors and the laptop and the silent house to study in cracks the exam and calls it pure merit. The Dalit kid who got in on reservation is told, to his face, in every comment section in this country, that he did not earn it, that he is lesser, that he is a quota. Same contempt Sandel describes, except we have a five thousand year old delivery system for it that the Americans never had.\n\nSo the meritocrat's lie that Sandel exposes, I made myself, has a second floor in India that he never visits. Here the man at the top did not even make himself by the rules of the meritocracy. He inherited the starting position, the symbolic capital, the surname, and then ran the meritocratic race from fifty metres ahead and collected the medal as proof of his superiority. Sandel says luck is the unearned thing the winner refuses to see. In India the unearned thing is not just luck. It is rank, banked over a thousand years, laundered through an entrance exam into something that now looks like merit and feels like justice.\n\nSandel diagnosed the disease for the West. He has no idea how much worse the patient is over here, where the new meritocracy did not replace the old hierarchy. It married it.\n\nRead it for the diagnosis, which is one of the sharpest of the last decade. Skip the solutions, which are thin. And read the whole thing twice if you are Indian, because he is describing your country far more accurately than he will ever know, and the second floor of the lie is the floor we all actually live on.",
            "pdf": ""
