            "title": "The WEIRDest People in the World",
            "author": "Joseph Henrich",
            "year": "2020",
            "teaser": "The first thing an Indian family wants to know about a marriage is the one thing this book says decides everything. Gotra. Caste. Sub caste. Community.…",
            "body": "The first thing an Indian family wants to know about a marriage is the one thing this book says decides everything. Gotra. Caste. Sub caste. Community. Same is preferred, different is negotiable, too different is a funeral. We treat this as tradition, harmless, grandma being grandma. Henrich wrote seven hundred pages to argue that this single question, who you are permitted to marry, is the master switch of an entire civilisation, the thing that quietly decides whether your society becomes rich, trusting, individual and free, or stays a clan locked in on itself for three thousand years. We have been answering that question the same way on purpose since before the Buddha, and Henrich is the man who explains, better than anyone in this whole stack, exactly what that answer costs.\n\nAnd I have to be honest before I start, because this is the one book in this entire run of reviews that argues against me. I have spent every one of these telling you the operating system is permanent. Caste is forever. The iron law is iron. We auctioned the future and the machine does not care who holds the lever. Henrich walks in and says no. The operating system is not hardware. It is software. It was installed once, by accident, over a thousand years, and what was installed can in principle be uninstalled. This is the hopeful book. So I read it twice, because a man who only reads what confirms his despair is just a WhatsApp uncle with a bigger vocabulary, and I owe you the strongest case against my own pessimism before I tell you whether it survives.\n\nWEIRD. We studied the strangest humans alive and called them human nature.\n\nStart with the joke at the centre of the book, because it is a real and damning one.\n\nAlmost everything psychology claims to know about the human mind was discovered by studying a tiny, freakish slice of our species. American university undergraduates, mostly. Henrich and his colleagues coined the acronym for that slice. WEIRD. Western, Educated, Industrialised, Rich, Democratic. And then they did the thing nobody had bothered to do, which was check whether these people were representative of humanity.\n\nThey are not. On trait after trait, WEIRD people are not the centre of the human distribution. They are the far outer edge. The global outlier. We built a science of the human mind by studying the least typical humans on earth and assuming they were the default setting. That alone is worth the book, because it quietly torches a century of confident social science.\n\nWhat WEIRD psychology actually is, and why it is so rare.\n\nSlow down here, because the whole argument hangs on what makes these people weird.\n\nThe WEIRD mind is intensely individualistic. It locates the self inside the person, as a bundle of personal attributes, choices and dispositions, rather than inside a web of relationships and roles. It thinks analytically, sorting the world into objects and categories and rules, instead of holistically, seeing the world as fields of relationships and context. It runs on guilt, an internal standard you violate privately, rather than shame, the external eye of the community watching whether you brought dishonour. It believes in free will and personal responsibility. It is low on conformity and deference to elders and tradition.\n\nAnd the big ones, the ones that matter for everything that follows. The WEIRD mind trusts strangers. It is impersonally prosocial, meaning it will be fair and honest to an anonymous person it will never meet again, a person from no kin group, no village, no community of its own. It is universalist, applying the same rule to everyone regardless of who they are to you. And it is strikingly low on nepotism and in group favouritism. It does not automatically privilege blood.\n\nRead that list and then look around you, because almost every trait on it is the opposite of how most of humanity has lived for most of history, and the opposite of how this subcontinent runs right now. That is the point. WEIRD is not better. Henrich is careful and repeats it. WEIRD is weird. It is the deviation that needs explaining, not the norm.\n\nThe puzzle, and the answer nobody expected. The clan, and the institution that killed it.\n\nSo where did this strange psychology come from, and why is it recent, only a few centuries old in full bloom? Here is Henrich's mechanism, and it is the most original thing in modern social science.\n\nThe human default, the thing we ran on for almost all of our existence, is what he calls intensive kinship. The clan. The lineage. Cousin marriage to keep wealth and women inside the family. Arranged marriage. Polygamy. Ancestor worship. Collective property. Collective responsibility, where the whole family is liable for what one member does and the whole family takes revenge when one member is wronged. This structure produces a very specific mind. Loyal to the in group, suspicious of the stranger, conformist, shame driven, deferential to elders, nepotistic by reflex. Not because those people are morally worse. Because that mind is the correct, optimised output of that family structure. In a clan world, trusting the stranger over your cousin is not virtue, it is suicide.\n\nNow the move. In Western Europe, starting around the year 500 and running for roughly a thousand years, one institution systematically dismantled intensive kinship, and it did so without having any idea what it was doing. The Western Church. Henrich calls the package the Marriage and Family Program. The Church banned cousin marriage, and kept widening the ban until at its most extreme it reached out to sixth cousins, a genuinely insane radius that made it nearly impossible to marry anyone you were related to. It banned polygamy. It banned marrying your dead brother's widow. It discouraged adoption. It pushed the monogamous nuclear family, individual consent in marriage, and individual wills leaving property to whoever you chose rather than automatically to the lineage.\n\nWhy did the Church do this? Not out of genius and not out of a plan for modernity. Partly accident, partly self interest, and Henrich builds here on the older work of the anthropologist Jack Goody. Smash the clan and people die without close kin to inherit, and the property flows to the Church. Dissolve the lineages and you weaken the Church's rivals for loyalty. The Church became spectacularly rich and powerful by quietly demolishing the family structures that competed with it. It thought it was saving souls and consolidating itself. It was, by total accident, rewiring the European mind.\n\nThe consequence. Loose individuals, and the world they were forced to build.\n\nFollow what happens when you break the clan, because this is the payoff and it answers the question Acemoglu only half answered in the last review.\n\nTake a person and cut him loose from the lineage that used to be his entire safety net, his identity, his insurance, his everything. He now cannot fall back on cousins, because the Church made sure he barely has any in the relevant sense. So how does he survive and get ahead? He has to form bonds with strangers. With people chosen for shared interest, shared belief, shared skill, rather than shared blood. He has to learn to trust the unrelated.\n\nAnd out of that necessity grows the entire scaffolding of the modern West. Voluntary associations. Cities full of unrelated migrants. Guilds organised by craft not kin. Universities. Monasteries. Charter towns with rules that apply to every member equally because there is no dominant clan to bend them. Impersonal markets where you deal fairly with a stranger because reputation and law, not family, enforce the deal. The rule of law as a universal thing rather than kin justice and blood feud. Generalised trust. Individualism. The analytic mind. Guilt over shame.\n\nHere is the deepest claim, and it is the one that picks a direct fight with Acemoglu. The psychology came first and made the institutions possible. The institutionalists say get the rules right and prosperity follows. Henrich says you cannot just install the rules, because the rules run on a psychology, and that psychology has to be built first by centuries of changed family life. This is why, he argues, you cannot photocopy Denmark. You can copy its constitution onto paper in an afternoon. You cannot copy the thousand years of de clanning that taught its people to trust the stranger and apply the rule evenly. The paper Leviathan from the last review is a country that imported the institutions and never got the psychology.\n\nThe data, because he does not just tell a pretty story.\n\nThis would be a nice fable if it were only a fable, and Henrich knows it, so he buries you in evidence. He builds a Kinship Intensity Index, a way to measure how clan based a society is, and then runs it against everything. The result is brutal and consistent. The more intensive the kinship, the more cousin marriage, the more corruption, the more nepotism, the weaker the democracy, the lower the trust in strangers, the stronger the in group favouritism, the more blood feud and honour violence. And the cleaner part. He can show it inside Europe, even inside Italy, where regions that came under the Church and its cousin marriage ban earlier and longer are measurably more WEIRD today, more trusting, more impersonal, less nepotistic, than regions the Church reached late or weakly. The dose of de clanning predicts the psychology centuries later. That is not a vibe. That is a gradient.\n\nHe also leans on his own famous fieldwork, the economic games played across many small societies, showing that people from more market integrated, less clan bound communities play fairer with anonymous strangers, while people from intensive kinship societies, sensibly, keep the value inside the group. Fairness to strangers is not human nature. It is a WEIRD acquired taste.\n\nThe Reformation, literacy, and the collective brain.\n\nThe last movement of the book is how this psychology, once built, detonated into the modern world. Competition between all those voluntary groups, cities, guilds, orders, states, drove a relentless churn of institutional experiment. And then the Reformation lands the accelerator. Protestants insisted every believer read the Bible himself, which spread mass literacy across whole populations for the first time, and Henrich makes the startling, physical point that reading rewires the brain, reorganising it, pushing facial recognition toward one hemisphere to make room for processing text. A society of readers is a society of altered brains.\n\nAnd underneath it all sits the idea from his earlier work, the collective brain. Innovation is not lonely genius. It is a function of how many minds you have connected and how freely ideas flow between them. Bigger, denser, more interconnected networks of people invent faster, not because they are smarter but because more recombination happens. The West did not out think the world. It out connected it, because de clanning let strangers pool their minds.\n\nThe part that pairs against my pessimism, which is why you sent me this book.\n\nNow the philosophical core, and the reason this review exists in this particular stack.\n\nHenrich's argument cuts two ways and you have to hold both.\n\nOne edge sounds even more fatalistic than Michels. If your entire psychology, your capacity for trust and fairness and individualism, is constructed by a thousand years of family structure, then a society without that history is psychologically locked out. You cannot vote your way to a WEIRD mind. The cage is not just laws, it is wiring laid down over centuries. That is a colder determinism than anything I said in the last five reviews.\n\nBut the other edge is the antidote, and it is the whole hope of the book, so hear it clearly. The thing that built the WEIRD mind was not genes. It was not race. It was not some eternal civilisational essence. It was culture, specifically family structure, and culture is software. It was installed. By accident. By an institution that did not even understand the program it was running. And the iron rule of anything installed is that it can be uninstalled and a new one written. Henrich is the man who took the deepest, most permanent seeming feature of a civilisation, its very psychology, and proved it was contingent, recent, and changeable. That is a hammer aimed straight at every sentence I have written about permanence. If the European mind is a patch the Church accidentally shipped, then nothing about any people's mind is destiny. The operating system is software all the way down.\n\nThe part that is about us, and it is the most exact fit in the whole stack.\n\nBecause here is the thing that should stop you cold. The villain of Henrich's book, the thing he names as the master variable holding societies in the clan trap, is intensive kinship and endogamy and cousin marriage. And India is the global capital of exactly that. Not a participant. The world champion.\n\nCaste is endogamy. That is not a side feature of caste, it is the definition of it. A caste is a group you must marry inside. We did not just keep intensive kinship, we sacralised it, codified it, ranked it, and ran it for three thousand years across every religion on the subcontinent, and we never, not once, had the institution that broke it in Europe. We never had a Church that smashed the clan. Our religious institutions did the precise opposite. They are the clan, in robes, enforcing the boundary. We are the highest kinship intensity civilisation on earth and we built priests to guard the wall instead of priests to tear it down.\n\nSo look what Henrich's framework does. It explains, more completely than Acemoglu or Michels could, why our modern institutions keep getting eaten. The party becomes a family firm because the psychology underneath it was never de clanned, so handing power to your blood is not corruption, it is the operating system functioning exactly as designed. Nepotism here is not a glitch. It is the mind doing what intensive kinship trained it to do, which is privilege blood over the stranger, every time, automatically, without guilt, because in a clan world that is correct behaviour. Impersonal fairness, the one trait that builds trust, markets and rule of law, is the single trait a caste society is structurally built to never produce. You cannot run an honest impersonal institution with minds that were manufactured to see the in group as everything and the stranger as nothing. We imported the institutions on paper and ran them on clan psychology and then act shocked when they behave like clans.\n\nAnd now the hope, because this is the book that finally lets me offer some. If Henrich is right, then our dysfunction is not genetic, not eternal, not the curse I have been half implying for five reviews. It is the predictable output of a kinship structure that no institution ever dismantled. Which means the cure exists, is known, and is embarrassingly simple to name. It is marrying out of the clan. Inter caste, inter gotra, inter community marriage is not a soft liberal nicety to feel good about. In Henrich's framework it is the single most load bearing structural reform a human society can perform, the literal mechanism, the exact lever, that built the entire modern world by accident in Europe. Every inter caste marriage is one small Marriage and Family Program running by hand. The thing is not mysterious. We know what built the West. It was people being made to marry strangers.\n\nAnd now the catch, because I am still me. The West did it through an institution that had the power, the reach, and a thousand uninterrupted years to do it. Who has that here? The state is a paper Leviathan, despotic against the citizen and absent against the custom, as we established. Society itself is the cage and is fanatically committed to the wall. There is no Indian Church that wants to break endogamy. The strongest social forces in this country exist specifically to enforce it. Which is why, in Henrich's cold anthropological frame, the honour killing is not random savagery. It is the immune system of intensive kinship doing its job, killing the WEIRD mutation, the love marriage across the line, before it can spread the patch to the next generation. The one act that builds the modern world is the one act this civilisation reserves its deepest violence to prevent. We are not missing the cure. We are murdering the people who try to take it.\n\nSo Henrich both refutes my fatalism and explains, with perfect precision, why the patch will not run here. It is software, not hardware, so we are not doomed forever, and that genuinely loosened something in me. But the only force ever shown capable of rewriting that software is a millennium long institutional assault on the family, and we have no installer and our operating system actively defends itself against the upgrade.\n\nWhere the book is weak, because it is.\n\nI will not canonise it just because it dented my pessimism. The biggest problem is that the Church did it is too clean, monocausal, almost too satisfying. A thousand years of European history compressed into one mechanism, cousin marriage bans, is elegant the way the institutions does everything in the last review was elegant, and elegance in social science is usually a warning. He underweights everything the other books in this stack stressed, Roman law, geography, the plague, coal, and above all colonial extraction, the small detail that the WEIRD West also got rich by looting the clan societies it now lectures. The kinship index correlations are real and consistent, but they are correlations, and a thousand years is a long time for other things to ride along with cousin marriage.\n\nSecond, and watch for this, the book carries a polished new Eurocentrism. Henrich insists WEIRD is not better, only weird, and I believe he means it. But the entire gravity of seven hundred pages pulls toward explaining the glorious rise and special mind of the West, and it can read as the old how the West won story given an anthropologist's respectable accent. The framing flatters exactly the readers most likely to buy it.\n\nThird, the very determinism that makes it powerful makes it close to useless as instruction, the standard disease of this whole stack. If the cure is a thousand year program run by an institution you do not have, then naming the cure is almost a cruelty. He hands you the master key and then explains it only fits a lock that took ten centuries to install.\n\nThe verdict.\n\nRead it. It is the most important social science book of the last decade and the only one in this entire run that fights back against the despair the others build, because it proves the thing I kept calling permanent is in fact contingent, recent, accidental and made of culture, which means changeable. Once you have intensive kinship and impersonal prosociality and the collective brain in your head, you cannot unsee them, and your own country snaps into focus with a clarity that is genuinely painful. It explains the nepotism, the family parties, the eaten institutions, the worship of blood, the violence against the love marriage, all of it, as one coherent output of one structure we refuse to touch.\n\nHold against it the monocausal neatness, the dressed up triumphalism, and the cruelty of a cure measured in centuries.\n\nBut here is why I am ending this one differently from all the others. In every previous review I closed by saying I would love to be wrong, knowing I was probably right. This is the first book that gives me an actual reason to think I might be wrong in the direction of hope, and I am not too proud to say it loosened the iron a little. It moved the real question off whether we are doomed forever, which Henrich shows we are not, and onto whether we will ever build or tolerate the one force capable of doing what the Church did by accident.\n\nAnd the answer to that is sitting, right now, in the first question every Indian family asks about a marriage. The most radical, most modernising, most genuinely nation building act available to an Indian is not a startup, not a policy, not a satellite, not a frontier model we will never own. It is marrying the person your family told you that you cannot. Henrich proved that is the lever that built the modern world. We call it the one unforgivable thing, and we kill for it. The cure has been in the matrimonial column the whole time. We just keep reading it as a warning instead of a way out.",
