            "teaser": "There is a town called Nogales sitting on the Arizona Mexico border. One fence runs through the middle of it. Same desert on both sides. Same…",
            "body": "There is a town called Nogales sitting on the Arizona Mexico border. One fence runs through the middle of it. Same desert on both sides. Same people, same surnames, same food, same Spanish, often the same families with cousins on either side of the wire. North of the fence the average household earns three times what it earns south of the fence, the kids stay in school longer, the old people live longer, nobody is scared of the police. South of the fence, the opposite. Same dirt. Same blood. Different country.\n\nThat is the whole question these two books exist to answer, and it is the only question in social science that actually matters. Why are some places rich and free and some places poor and caged, when the people are identical. Acemoglu and Robinson spent two fat books answering it, won the Nobel for it in 2024, and the answer is so simple it is almost insulting. It is the rules. It is the institutions. Not the weather, not the religion, not the IQ, not the culture. The rules.\n\nLet me walk you through both, because they are really one argument in two halves. The first book asks why nations get rich. The second asks why nations get free. They are not the same question and the authors are honest enough to admit the first book did not fully answer the second, which is rarer than you think among people this famous.\n\nWhy Nations Fail\n\nFirst they kill the comfortable explanations.\n\nBefore they build anything they spend the opening burning down every excuse you have ever heard, and this is the best part of the book because the excuses are the things everyone believes.\n\nThe geography excuse. Poor countries are poor because they are hot, tropical, disease ridden, badly located. Dead, they say. Look at Nogales. Same geography, wildly different outcome. Look at the two Koreas, one satellite photo, one half lit up like a circuit board at night and the other half pure black, same peninsula, same people, same mountains, one fence. Geography did not draw that line. Men did.\n\nThe culture excuse. This is the favourite of every dinner table in every rich country and every self hating one. They are poor because their culture is lazy, fatalistic, corrupt, not hardworking like ours. Also dead. The same Korean culture produced the circuit board and the black hole. The culture did not change at the 38th parallel. The rules did.\n\nThe ignorance excuse. They are poor because their leaders just do not know the right economic policy, and if we send enough World Bank consultants with the correct PowerPoint they will fix it. The most arrogant of the three and also dead. The leaders of poor countries are not poor because they are confused. They are poor on purpose, because the system that keeps the country poor is the exact same system that keeps those leaders rich. They know precisely what they are doing. Ignorance is not the problem. Incentives are.\n\nThis demolition alone is worth the book, and notice the move, because it is the right one. They refuse the lazy individual level answer and go to the structure. It is never the lazy native or the stupid minister. It is the operating system everyone is running inside.\n\nThen the one distinction the whole thing rests on. Inclusive vs extractive.\n\nHere is the engine. Every institution, economic or political, is one of two kinds.\n\nExtractive institutions are built so a small group at the top can extract everything from everyone below. The wealth, the labour, the land, the future. The colony, the plantation, the dictatorship, the rigged monopoly handed to the dictator's nephew. They are designed to funnel up.\n\nInclusive institutions are built so most people can participate, own things securely, start a business, get educated, sign a contract that a court will actually enforce, and keep most of what they make. Power is spread out, not hoarded.\n\nAnd the magic word that connects everything is creative destruction. Schumpeter's idea. The new kills the old. The car kills the horse cart. The streaming service kills the video store. Progress is always somebody's business dying. Inclusive societies allow this. They let the new guy destroy the old guy, and that churn is exactly what makes them rich, because innovation is permitted to win.\n\nExtractive societies cannot allow it, and this is the deepest point in the book. The elite in an extractive system blocks innovation on purpose, because the new technology, the new business, the new class of people getting rich, all of it threatens the existing top dogs. The Ottoman sultans banned the printing press for centuries. The Austrian and Russian emperors blocked railways because moving people around freely was a threat to control. They were not stupid. They correctly understood that progress would cost them their position, and they chose their position over their country's future every single time. An extractive elite will keep the whole nation poor rather than risk being overtaken inside it. They would rather own all of a small pie than a slice of a huge one, because the huge one comes with rivals.\n\nThat is the cleanest explanation of why poor countries stay poor that anyone has written. The people running them are not failing. They are succeeding at a different game, the game of staying on top, and keeping the country down is how you win that game.\n\nCritical junctures and drift. Why England and not China.\n\nSo how does any society ever escape. Their answer is honest and a little unsatisfying, which is a point in its favour because the real answer probably is unsatisfying.\n\nSmall differences plus big shocks. Societies drift, slowly, with tiny institutional differences accumulating almost invisibly. Then a critical juncture hits, a massive shock, the Black Death, the discovery of the Americas, the opening of Atlantic trade. And which way a society jumps at that shock depends on those tiny prior differences. Same shock, opposite results, because the starting positions were a hair apart.\n\nTheir headline case is 1688, the Glorious Revolution in England, when Parliament finally chained the king, secured property rights, opened the economy, and unleashed the Industrial Revolution a century later. England fell into inclusiveness almost by accident, by a balance of forces where nobody could fully win, and that accident is why a damp little island ran the planet for two hundred years.\n\nThe iron law of oligarchy. Why revolutions usually change nothing.\n\nThis is the most depressing and most useful chapter, so do not skip it. They show, case after case, that overthrowing an extractive regime almost never produces freedom. It produces a new extractive regime with new faces. The Bolsheviks toppled the Tsar and built something more extractive than the Tsar ever managed. African independence movements toppled colonial extraction and the new local big men simply moved into the same palace and ran the same extraction with a national flag on it. They call it the iron law of oligarchy. The new boss inherits the old machine and discovers he rather likes it. The machine does not care whose hands are on the levers. It extracts either way.\n\nThis is the single most important warning in the book and the one every angry young person needs tattooed somewhere. Removing the tyrant is not the same as removing the tyranny. If you leave the extractive machine standing and just change the operator, you have done nothing. You have held the balls of a different Mongol.\n\nThe Narrow Corridor\n\nThe first book had a hole and they knew it. It said inclusive institutions make you rich, but it did not really say how a society gets and keeps them, or what liberty actually requires. So seven years later they wrote the better book, the one that answers the harder question. Not why nations get rich. Why nations get free.\n\nThe corridor. Liberty lives in a thin gap and almost everyone falls out.\n\nThe central image, and it is a good one. Freedom is not a destination you reach and then relax. Freedom is a narrow corridor you have to keep running down, and there is a cliff on each side.\n\nFall off the left side and you get the Absent Leviathan. The state is too weak or does not exist. No central power to stop the strong from eating the weak. This sounds like freedom to a certain kind of libertarian fool, but it is the opposite, because where the state is absent, you are not free, you are ruled by something older and worse. You are ruled by custom, by the clan, by the feud, by what they brilliantly call the cage of norms. Tradition becomes the tyrant. You cannot marry who you want, leave your assigned role, or live differently, not because a king forbids it but because the village, the caste, the elders, the honour code forbid it, and there is no higher power to appeal to. The cage of norms is a prison with no warden and no door, and it can be more total than any dictatorship.\n\nFall off the right side and you get the Despotic Leviathan. The state is too strong. It crushes society flat and calls the silence order. China is their headline case. A genuinely capable state, builds roads, lifts millions out of poverty, delivers results, and owns you completely. It will give you prosperity and take your liberty as the price, and it never asks if you wanted to make that trade.\n\nAnd in the thin gap between the absent and the despotic runs the corridor, where you get the only thing that actually produces liberty. The Shackled Leviathan. A state strong enough to enforce order and crush the cage of norms, and a society strong enough to chain that very state and stop it becoming a despot. Both strong. Both fighting. Neither winning.\n\nThe Red Queen. Why you can never stop running.\n\nThe mechanism that keeps you in the corridor is taken from Alice through the looking glass, where the Red Queen tells Alice you have to run as fast as you can just to stay in the same place. State and society have to keep getting stronger together, racing each other forever, locked in a balanced struggle. The state grows its capacity, so society has to grow its ability to check it, so the state grows again. The day one side stops running, you fall out of the corridor. If the state outruns society, despotism. If society blocks the state from ever forming, the cage of norms and chaos. Liberty is not a treaty you sign once. It is a fight you re sign every morning, forever, and the moment you get tired and stop, you lose it.\n\nThis is the truest thing in either book. Freedom is not a building you finish. It is a fire you have to keep feeding, and it goes out the second you decide it is safe to sleep.\n\nThe part that is about us, which they wrote and then walked past\n\nNow here is where I get loud, because both authors look directly at India, describe the most important thing about it correctly, and then move on as if it were just one more case study, when for us it is the entire diagnosis.\n\nIndia, in their own framework, is the proof that the cage of norms and a modern state can exist at the same time, in the same body, which their tidy corridor model is not really built to handle. We have elections, courts, a constitution, a Leviathan that is loud on paper. And underneath it, completely intact, runs the oldest cage of norms on the planet. Caste. A prison with no warden and no door, exactly as they describe it, except ours is five thousand years old and survived every empire and every reform thrown at it.\n\nThey even have the perfect term for our state, which they apply to others but which fits us like a glove. The paper Leviathan. A state that looks enormous and capable on the letterhead and is actually weak and absent in the one job that matters, which is breaking the cage and protecting the individual from his own community. The Indian state will land on the moon and then fail to stop a village panchayat from murdering a couple for marrying across caste. It is despotic where it should be light, the raids, the arrests, the bulldozers, and absent exactly where liberty needs it, the moment the cage of norms starts crushing someone. Strong against the citizen, useless against the custom. The worst of both cliffs at once.\n\nAnd here is the thing their model misses about us, the thing it genuinely cannot see. Their whole theory assumes a strong society is a good thing, a check on the state, the thing that keeps you in the corridor. But what happens when the strong society is itself the prison. In India society is incredibly strong. It is just strong in the service of the cage. The community has immense power, and it uses that power not to chain the state and free the individual, but to crush the individual on behalf of tradition. Our society is not a check on tyranny. Large parts of it are the tyranny, with no king required. Acemoglu and Robinson built a model where you need society strong and state strong and balanced. They did not fully reckon with a place where the strength of society is the thing eating your freedom, where the state, if anything, is sometimes the only escape hatch a low caste person has from the village that owns him. That inverts their whole picture and they breeze past it in a few pages.\n\nWhere the books are weak, because they are\n\nI am not going to canonise this just because it has a Nobel on it.\n\nThe biggest problem with Why Nations Fail is that institutions becomes a magic word that explains everything and therefore explains nothing. Why is this country rich. Inclusive institutions. How do you know they are inclusive. Because the country is rich. Run that in a circle a few times and you notice it is a snake eating its own tail. Almost any outcome can be relabelled after the fact as the right kind of institution. A theory that can absorb every result is not a theory, it is a filing system.\n\nSecond, it is a magnificent description and a near useless instruction manual. They will tell you with total clarity that you need inclusive institutions and the rule of law and creative destruction. They will not, cannot, tell you how a poor caged country actually builds those things starting from Tuesday. Their own answer is basically luck. Small drift plus a lucky shock plus jumping the right way. Which is honest, but it means the book is a brilliant autopsy and a blank prescription pad. Same disease as every great diagnostician. They can name your cancer to the cell and they hand you a pamphlet for the cure.\n\nThird, the China bet. Why Nations Fail essentially predicted that China's extractive growth would stall because you cannot get sustained innovation without inclusion. It has been over a decade. China kept growing, kept innovating, built the despotic Leviathan into a machine that does creative destruction under an iron fist, which their model said should not really be possible. The authors will say wait, it is unsustainable, give it time. Maybe. The slowdown is real now in 2026. But a theory that keeps saying just wait is a theory buying itself out of being wrong on credit.\n\nAnd the corridor itself, elegant as it is, has the same slipperiness. Did a country fall out of the corridor, or did we only decide it was in the corridor because it stayed free. The line is drawn after the race is run. It is a beautiful map you can only finish drawing once you already know where everyone ended up.\n\nThe verdict\n\nRead both, in order, and treat them as one book in two volumes. Why Nations Fail gives you the single most powerful idea for seeing the world, that poverty is not an accident or a curse or a character flaw but a design, maintained on purpose by people it serves, and that the elite blocking your country's future are not failing at their job, they are succeeding at a different one. The Narrow Corridor gives you the harder and truer follow up, that freedom is not a thing you win once but a fight you have to keep fighting forever, balanced on a knife between the despot and the cage, and that the day you stop running you fall.\n\nFor everyone they are essential. For Indians they are a mirror the authors did not fully realise they were holding up, because we are the country where the cage of norms wears the clothes of a strong society, where the paper Leviathan is despotic to the citizen and absent against the custom, and where the oldest extractive machine on earth, caste, learned to survive inside a democracy by simply refusing to be on the ballot.\n\nThe iron law of oligarchy is the line I would leave you with, slightly bent for home use. Removing the man at the top changes nothing if you leave the machine running. We keep changing the operator and acting surprised that the extraction continues. The machine does not care who holds the lever. It was never about the lever.\n\nI would love to be told we are further down the corridor than I think. Look at any honour killing verdict, any caste comment section, any village that still decides who its women may love, and tell me with a straight face we ever fully entered it.",
